      <hedline>
        <hl1>How to Pay Teachers</hl1>
      </hedline>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>On the matter of retaining and rewarding teachers (letter, April 24), basing teachers' pay on what administrators deem good teaching leads to charges of favoritism and causes tension and morale problems. If salary is to be determined by results like higher test scores, those who teach in deprived areas would themselves be financially deprived.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>On the matter of retaining and rewarding teachers (letter, April 24), basing teachers' pay on what administrators deem good teaching leads to charges of favoritism and causes tension and morale problems. If salary is to be determined by results like higher test scores, those who teach in deprived areas would themselves be financially deprived.</p>
        <p>Having taught in an urban public school system (Chicago), I have found that teachers accept length of service, further education and training as criteria for increases in salary.</p>
        <p>MORRIS FINDER  Loudonville, N.Y., April 24, 2001</p>
      </block>
